<subSubSection id="49C942EEFFB5396DEBD2C61DFC6F59AD" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="016C1165FFB5396DEBD2C61DFEAA5A7E" blockId="27.[227,341,302,328]" box="[227,341,302,328]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<heading id="5A24A609FFB5396DEBD2C61DFEAA5A7E" bold="true" box="[227,341,302,328]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFB5396DEBD2C61DFEAA5A7E" bold="true" box="[227,341,302,328]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FFB5396DEBD2C66DFC6F59AD" blockId="27.[227,1438,350,668]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
Otoliths of the extant 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FFB5396DEAC0C66DFBEA5A4E" authority="(Regan, 1912)" baseAuthorityName="Regan" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[497,1045,350,376]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Heterenchelyidae" genus="Pythonichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microphthalmus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFB5396DEAC0C66DFC9F5A4E" box="[497,864,350,376]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Pythonichthys microphthalmus</emphasis>
(Regan, 1912)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FFB5396DEF64C66CFA635A4E" authority="(Regan, 1912)" baseAuthorityName="Regan" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[1109,1436,350,376]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Heterenchelyidae" genus="Pythonichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anguilliformes" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrurus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFB5396DEF64C66CFB195A4E" box="[1109,1254,351,376]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">P. macrurus</emphasis>
(Regan, 1912)
</taxonomicName>
were figured by 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FFB5396DEA94C6B1FD4D5AAA" author="Nolf &amp; Stringer" box="[421,690,386,412]" firstAuthor="Nolf" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="41 - 81" refId="ref56252" refString="Nolf D. &amp; Stringer G. L. 1992. Neogene paleontology in the northern Dominican Republic 14. Otoliths of teleostean fishes. Bulletins of American Paleontology 102 (340): 41 - 81." type="journal article" year="1992">Nolf &amp; Stringer (1992</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 9 figs 14 and 15, respectively). This was overlooked in the overview of 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FFB5396DEA44C694FDFC5AF7" author="Nolf" box="[373,515,423,449]" firstAuthor="Nolf" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" refId="ref55849" refString="Nolf D. 2013. The Diversity of Fish Otoliths, Past and Present. Royal Belgian Institute of Natural Sciences, Brussels." type="book" year="2013">Nolf (2013)</bibRefCitation>
, and not mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FFB5396DE821C694FBF15AF7" author="Ebersole" box="[784,1038,423,449]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Ebersole" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" refId="ref53603" refString="Ebersole J. A., Cicimurri D. J. &amp; Stringer G. L. 2019. Taxonomy and biostratigraphy of the elasmobranchs and bony fishes (Chondrichthyes and Osteichthyes) of the lower - to - middle Eocene (Ypresian to Bartonian) Claiborne Group in Alabama, USA, including an analysis of otoliths. European Journal of" type="book" year="2019">
Ebersole 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFB5396DE84DC694FC4F5AF7" box="[892,944,423,449]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">et al</emphasis>
. (2019)
</bibRefCitation>
, but a comparison with the abovementioned figures of 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FFB5396DEAD4C6F8FD025AD3" author="Nolf &amp; Stringer" box="[485,765,459,485]" firstAuthor="Nolf" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="41 - 81" refId="ref56252" refString="Nolf D. &amp; Stringer G. L. 1992. Neogene paleontology in the northern Dominican Republic 14. Otoliths of teleostean fishes. Bulletins of American Paleontology 102 (340): 41 - 81." type="journal article" year="1992">Nolf &amp; Stringer (1992)</bibRefCitation>
suggests that their generic attribution is plausible. This species was represented by 
<specimenCount id="17D5DAECFFB5396DE91DC6DCFD33593F" box="[556,716,495,521]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="generic">90 specimens</specimenCount>
in the upper Eocene Yazoo Clay by 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FFB5396DEFB3C6DCFA67593F" author="Nolf &amp; Stringer" box="[1154,1432,495,521]" firstAuthor="Nolf" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 23" refId="ref56290" refString="Nolf D. &amp; Stringer G. L. 2003. Late Eocene (Priabonian) fish otoliths from the Yazoo Clay at Copenhagen, Louisiana. Louisiana Geological Survey Geological Pamphlet 13: 1 - 23." type="journal article" year="2003">Nolf &amp; Stringer (2003)</bibRefCitation>
, but it represented less than 2% of the total assemblage. Although widely distributed in the Claiborne and Jackson groups, it typically represents only a small percentage of the assemblages. The genus is also known from the Paleocene Clayton Formation in 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FFB5396DE815C56FFC6E5940" box="[804,913,604,630]" country="United States of America" name="Arkansas" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Arkansas</collectingRegion>
in unusually large numbers (24% of the total assemblage) according to 
<bibRefCitation id="65426C94FFB5396DE925C5B2FC7259AD" author="Schwarzhans &amp; Stringer" box="[532,909,641,667]" firstAuthor="Schwarzhans" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" pagination="395 - 446" refId="ref57092" refString="Schwarzhans W. &amp; Stringer G. L. 2020. Fish otoliths from the late Maastrichtian Kemp Clay (Texas, USA) and the early Danian Clayton Formation (Arkansas, USA) and an assessment of extinction and survival of teleost lineages across the K - Pg boundary based on otoliths. Rivista italiana di Paleontologia e Stratigraphia 126: 395 - 446. https: // doi. org / 10.13130 / 2039 - 4942 / 13425" type="journal article" year="2020">Schwarzhans &amp; Stringer (2020)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
